\ul\b\fs28 2.5 - Hyperlinks\par
\fs22 Introduction to hyperlinks\ulnone\b0\par
Hyperlink is any text or image we can click and it will take us to another page. This page can be:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 another web page\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}a bookmark (specific part of the web page)\line We learned about using the id attribute as a link target in the unit about attributes earlier. If we have a section in our page, we can link to that section using the value of its id attribute, preceded by the number sign\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}a local link (another part of the same website)\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}an email\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b Why we should use text over image links\b0\par
When it comes to hyperlinks, we should try to use text intead of images when possible.\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 Images are not as well understood or recognized as text\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Text is better for accessibility\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}If we have text in an image like the buy now button, search engines do not recognize text in images\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b Best practices\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 Apply hyperlinks to short phrases. it is unusual to see the link tag used around the whole paragraph\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Make link phrase meaningful. Aboid phrases like 'Click here' or 'Read More'. Click here to get help is redundant when we can create a link around the phrase 'get help'. The link is an indication that it should be clicked\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Don't use short link text. It is easy to miss the 'blue' hyperlink if it is used on one word or character and is hard for users to click using touch screen\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Appearance - links have a default appearance in most browsers, blue and underlined. We should ensure no other text in our page is underlined so as to avoid confusing the user. They might get frustrated trying to click text that they think is a link.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}If we choose to have image links, it should have alt text that descripbes the purpose of the link instead of the image being used - describe the target link\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b Anchor element\b0\par
The hyperlink tag element is simply <a>, and it is called the anchor element. Here is how it is used:\par
<a href="webpage.html">Bla bla link text</a>\par
\par
The anchor element should not be confused with the <link> tag. The <link> tag is used to define a link between a document and an external resource like an external style sheet. We will learn more about the <link> tag in the next chapter.\par
\par
If the link has not been clicked, it will be blue and underlined. Now, if we click on the link and then come back to where we were at the start we will see that a visited link looks purple and underlined. Apart from unvisited and visited links, there is also a status called active link. A link becomes active when the user is clicking on it. During this time, the link will be red and underlined.\par
\par
The a tag can surround text or an image. We can even use the anchore element to add our email address under the contacts section of our webpage. Nevertheless, we shold probably avoid using hyperlinks for email addresses:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 The email address usually opens up on the default email client on the user's computer which they might not use.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Providing our email address in  our web page directly as text or a hyperlink will expose it. Bots or spam crawlers can be used to search the Web to pick up email addresses for spam. We should avoid this if possible and use contact forms instead.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\ul\b Attributes: href and target\ulnone\b0\par
\b The href attribute\b0\par
The only attribute we have seen thus far in this chapter of hyperlinks is href. href points to the URL that the link should jump to. Though it is an optional attribute, without it, the <a> tag will not be a hyperlink because it has obviously no idea where to jump to. The href attribute takes a URL. This URL can be in the form of:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 a link to an external Web site\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}a link to a page or file within the same web site\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}link to an element on the same page. The element, is referenced using its ID.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}protocols such as mailto: -> for email addresses.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b The target attribute\b0\par
target specified the destination where the linked URL in href should be opened. It can take a variety of different values, but for our purposes we'll focus on the two below:\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 _self -> in the same view where the link resides. If no target is spcified, this is the default behaviour.\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}In a new window or tab. This is very convenient if we want to link the user to a web page without having the current one disappear. By clicking on the previous window or tab, they can redirect to the page where the link is.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\ul\b Attributes: media and download\b0\par
\ulnone\b The media attribute\b0\par
The media attribute was introduced in HTML5. We will look at it briefly here. It is used to specify what kind of media or device the URL we link to in hred is optimized for. The URL could be targeted for special devices like projectors, speech synthesizers or pages meant to be printed. It is useful if we want to cater our target document that the URL points to a particular device type.\par
\par
Imagine we have a page scattered with multipole images and we want to display this page on a handheld device. Handheld devices are known to have small screen and reduce the size of images. So the media attribute allows us to tell the anchor element that this page is targeted for handheld devices. We do this by providing a value for the attribute. This value could be any media query and is a combination of device type and media rendering values.\par
\par
Let's look at another example - we could create a print link to a long content heavy page that will redirect us to a print version of the same. We want this print version to be formatted into one page ideal for printing and with resolution of 250 dpi. Here is how the HTML5 code would look like:\par
<a href="blabla" media="print and (resolution:250dpi)">Bla bla</a?\par
\par
\b The download attribute\b0\par
The download attribute is also new in HTML5 and it makes a link download a file insted of navigate to another location. It takes in the filename as value but the value is optional. So the download attribute can be specified in the following ways:\par
<a href="/assets/hello.txt" download>\par
\par
If we do not specify a value for download, it will download the file with name unchanged. Else it will download the file with file name modified according to value specified.\par
